{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 23:04:04.078490", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Thanks — I reviewed the diagnosis and submitted the solution.\n\nSummary of submission\n- is_anomaly: true\n- faulty_devices: [\"server_access_router\"]\n- root_cause_name: [\"ospf_area_misconfiguration\"]\n\nRecommended remediation (concise)\n1. On server_access_router, remove or narrow the \"network 10.200.0.0/24 area 0\" OSPF statement so the router does not advertise the whole backend subnet into the enterprise OSPF domain. Options:\n   - Remove the network statement and redistribute only the load-balancer IP (10.200.0.7) into OSPF (advertise a host route /32) if the load‑balancer should be reachable.\n   - Alternatively, configure OSPF passive interface for the bridge (br0) and redistribute specific addresses/prefixes as needed.\n\n2. If the 10.200.0.0/24 must remain advertised for other reasons, implement route filtering on server_access_router to advertise only the load‑balancer IP or a more specific prefix (e.g., 10.200.0.7/32), and/or apply ACLs on the router or upstream devices to block host subnets from directly reaching backend server IPs.\n\n3. Consider adding explicit IP ACLs on server_access_router inbound from user-facing interfaces (or on core edge routers) to block traffic from host subnets to 10.200.0.3–.6 while allowing traffic to 10.200.0.7.\n\nIf you want, I can produce exact FRR config snippets for the recommended changes (remove network statement, add ospf redistribute host route, sample route-map/ACL for filtering) and the specific CLI commands to apply them.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 2554, "output_tokens": 360, "total_tokens": 2914, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 1664}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 0}}}
